User survey for ImagingSociety 2025 - National MRI research infrastructure in Norway

Author

Dr. Athanasia M. Mowinckel

Published

October 18, 2025

Background

This report presents an analysis of the survey data collected for the national grant scheme application for MRI research infrastructure in Norway. The survey was designed to gather insights from the research community on the current use, needs, and challenges related to MRI for human research.

The following sections will present a summary of the key findings, including graphical representations of the quantitative data and a textual summary of the open-ended responses, with the help of the Gemini LMM.

Survey Results

Of the 66 responses, 30 participants reported they currently use MRI for research, 45% indicate a future interest in using the new MRI facility for their work.

Participant Demographics

This section provides an overview of the survey participants’ roles and institutions.

Research Areas

The survey respondents represent a diverse range of research areas, with a strong emphasis on cognitive neuroscience and neurology. Key themes that emerge include:

  • Cognitive Neuroscience: This is a prominent area, covering various aspects such as attention, decision-making, language, music, aging, and specific methodologies like pupillometry, eye-tracking, fNIRS, EEG, computational modelling and brain stimulation.
  • Neurology & Neurodegenerative Diseases: A significant number of responses focus on neurological conditions such as dementia, Alzheimer’s disease, stroke, multiple sclerosis, brain tumors, traumatic brain injury, epilepsy, and general neurodegeneration.
  • Mental Health & Psychiatry: Research areas also include mental disorders, psychotherapy, child and adolescent psychiatry, psychosis, mood disorders, anorexia nervosa, and the intersection of brain development and mental health.
  • Brain Imaging & Methods Development: Many respondents are involved in developing and applying various brain imaging techniques (MRI, fMRI, MRS, multimodal imaging), along with the development of new contrasts and methods for the spinal cord.
  • Specific Cognitive Functions & Processes: Several responses highlight research on memory, language, auditory processing, speech, spatial cognition, and decision-making.
  • Aging & Women’s Health: A notable area of focus involves research on healthy aging, dementia in the context of aging, menopause, and women’s health issues related to cognition and neurological function.
  • Other Specialized Areas: The survey also encompasses areas such as pain research, immunology, rehabilitation medicine, brain injury in sport, body image, autoimmune diseases, and even paleoclimatology using medical imaging techniques.

How MRI Would Enhance Research

Based on the survey responses, increased and improved access to MRI would significantly expand and enhance research across a wide range of fields. Here’s a summary:

  • Fundamental to Existing Research: For many researchers, MRI is already a core component of their work (e.g., neurology, oncology, brain stimulation, dementia, epilepsy, cognitive function, neurosurgery). Improved access would greatly facilitate their ability to collect data, conduct studies, and participate in multi-center collaborations.
  • Expanding Research Areas: Many researchers expressed that access to MRI would open up entirely new avenues of research. Examples included:
    • Studies on sexual dysfunction and brain activity.
    • Deeper understanding of bilingualism, aging, and menopause
    • Research on pain, treatment outcomes, and the pain matrix
    • Investigation of the menstrual cycle and hormonal fluctuations on the brain
    • Exploring the relationship between brain structure/function and pain/its treatment
    • Investigating the neural basis of cognition
    • Investigating biomarkers for ADHD in women
    • Visual representation
    • Relationship between brain structure/function and pain/its treatment
    • Neural network involved in cognition
    • Diagnosis of geohazards.
    • Effects of interventions on brain anatomy, plasticity and activity
    • Interacting with artificial agents
  • Improved Research Quality: Increased access allows for larger sample sizes, higher quality fMRI data, state-of-the-art studies, and the use of advanced MRI sequences. It would also enhance the ability to validate findings across populations and examine the effects of hormonal fluctuations.
  • Addressing Specific Barriers: Access issues currently limit the ability to run studies, especially in certain geographical areas (e.g., northern Norway). Lack of access also hinders grant applications and prevents participation in multi-center studies.
  • Translational Research & Clinical Impact: MRI is crucial for developing novel algorithms, testing them in a hospital setting, and making clinically relevant decisions. The ability to conduct research MRIs for clinical studies would also improve.
  • Supporting Future Researchers: Improved access would allow for more master’s and PhD theses to incorporate MRI, training the next generation of scientists.
  • Addressing Limited Capacity: Some researchers highlighted that even when MRI is already part of a study, the current limited capacity makes it difficult to obtain research MRIs.

In short, respondents indicated that better MRI access is vital for their research, will improve existing research, and open up avenues for entirely new studies across diverse fields, ultimately leading to a better understanding of the brain and its functions, and improving diagnostics and treatment for a variety of conditions.

Future Needs

This section analyzes which conditions are considered most important for the future of MRI research in Norway.

Summary of Free-text Comments

This section provides a summary of the open-ended comments, generated using the Gemini LMM.

These responses emphasize the need for enhanced MRI research infrastructure and accessibility in Norway. A key theme is the desire for dedicated research scanners, ideally located outside of hospitals and closer to university campuses, to facilitate innovative research approaches and prioritize research over clinical use. Respondents suggest establishing a collaborative network of MRI researchers, particularly in Tromsø, and ensuring consistent capabilities across all sites, potentially including mention and integration with initiatives like MMIV. Furthermore, accessible and routinely available scan times are crucial for researchers. Finally, the ambition to develop true population mapping through synchronized scanners across Norway, potentially incorporating lessons from initiatives like the UK Biobank, and acquiring at least one 7T scanner for specialized subcortical research are highlighted as aspirational goals.

Conclusion

In conclusion, the overwhelming response to this survey unequivocally demonstrates a critical need for increased access to dedicated research-focused MRI scanners across Norway. The data reveals significant limitations in current research capabilities due to restricted access, high costs, and insufficient scanner specifications. Participants from diverse institutions and research areas emphasized how improved access to advanced MRI technology would significantly enhance their research, enabling larger-scale studies, innovative methodologies, and collaborations both nationally and internationally. This groundswell of support underscores the urgent requirement for strategic investment in MRI infrastructure to propel Norwegian research to the forefront of scientific discovery and ultimately improve healthcare outcomes. Failure to address this need risks hindering scientific progress and diminishing Norway’s competitiveness in the global research landscape.
